00:00:01,040 --> 00:00:03,280
127 HOURS

2
00:00:04,480 --> 00:00:05,040
PROLOGUE

3
00:00:06,160 --> 00:00:07,280
You are going to die.

4
00:00:08,400 --> 00:00:12,880
I hear the voice in my head. 
I call it my first voice.

5
00:00:14,320 --> 00:00:21,200
It always comes after I've made some kind of 
mistake. Its words never help, they just make  

6
00:00:21,200 --> 00:00:29,920
me feel bad. So I wait for the second voice. Its 
words are calm and sensible and nearly always help  

7
00:00:29,920 --> 00:00:38,320
me. I wait, but tonight the second voice doesn't 
come. There is only silence, darkness and cold.

8
00:00:39,680 --> 00:00:47,360
In the first days, the second voice always came. 
It stopped me feeling sad, angry, or afraid.  

9
00:00:48,400 --> 00:00:52,000
It gave me ideas. It showed me things.  

10
00:00:53,120 --> 00:01:00,640
It brought me hope. I believed I could be free 
again. But, slowly, that voice disappeared.  

11
00:01:01,680 --> 00:01:08,560
My belief disappeared with it. Now there 
is only the first voice. It says the same  

12
00:01:08,560 --> 00:01:15,280
thing over and over again. Finally, I must 
accept the truth: I am going to die.
 
 
 

13
00:01:17,120 --> 00:01:17,840
CHAPTER ONE

14
00:01:18,960 --> 00:01:20,880
'The most beautiful place on Earth'

15
00:01:21,920 --> 00:01:29,040
It is Saturday, April the 26th, 
2003. My name is Aron Ralston.  

16
00:01:30,080 --> 00:01:37,680
I'm biking and hiking in Canyonlands National 
Park in southeast Utah, USA. Edward Abbey,  

17
00:01:37,680 --> 00:01:42,480
one of my favourite writers, described it 
as 'the most beautiful place on Earth'.  

18
00:01:43,680 --> 00:01:47,920
Right now, with the sun on my back 
and the wind in my hair, I agree.

19
00:01:49,440 --> 00:01:52,240
Today is the third day of an activity holiday.  

20
00:01:53,280 --> 00:01:58,800
It started on Thursday when I went climbing 
and skiing on Mount Soplis with my friend,  

21
00:01:58,800 --> 00:02:06,880
Brad. Yesterday, I biked the Slick Rock Trail, 
alone. It's not very long - only a little  

22
00:02:06,880 --> 00:02:12,240
over nineteen kilometres - but it's one of 
the most difficult bike trails in the US.  

23
00:02:13,600 --> 00:02:19,520
Today, my plan is to hike through Blue John and 
Horseshoe Canyons after biking to the trail.  

24
00:02:20,560 --> 00:02:24,640
I'll leave my bike at the end of the 
trail and hike back to the carpark.  

25
00:02:25,600 --> 00:02:28,880
I'll drive over in the truck 
and collect the bike later.

26
00:02:30,480 --> 00:02:35,840
After that, I'll drive to Goblin Valley, 
about eighty kilometres north of here.  

27
00:02:36,880 --> 00:02:42,800
My friends are having a party there. I 
hope I get some sleep because tomorrow  

28
00:02:42,800 --> 00:02:47,200
I want to hike the most popular trail 
in southern Utah - Little White Horse.

29
00:02:48,800 --> 00:02:53,040
I plan to spend the whole of Monday 
biking along the White Rim Trail.  

30
00:02:54,080 --> 00:02:58,880
The trail forms a rough circle of 175 kilometres.  

31
00:03:00,000 --> 00:03:07,040
It's not difficult and I should be able to finish 
in about eighteen hours. By Monday evening,  

32
00:03:07,040 --> 00:03:14,240
I'll be back in Aspen, Colorado. Aspen is famous 
for its mountains and the countryside around it.  

33
00:03:15,200 --> 00:03:22,080
It's a popular place for skiing. I live there and 
I work for Ute Mountaineer, a sports equipment  

34
00:03:22,080 --> 00:03:29,200
shop. Leona, one of the people I live and work 
with, is having a goodbye party on Monday night.  

35
00:03:30,320 --> 00:03:35,280
Now that winter is over, she's going 
to another town in Colorado to work  

36
00:03:35,280 --> 00:03:40,480
as a gardener for the summer. Her party 
will be a cool way to end my trip.
 
 

37
00:03:42,400 --> 00:03:43,360
00 hrs

38
00:03:45,120 --> 00:03:51,440
8.45 am I arrive at the Horseshoe Canyon 
carpark early in the morning, pull my bike  

39
00:03:51,440 --> 00:03:57,520
from the truck and lock the door. Then I check 
the time: eight forty-five in the morning.  

40
00:03:58,480 --> 00:04:03,440
As I start cycling, I wonder how quickly 
I can get to the start of the trail.

41
00:04:04,880 --> 00:04:08,080
I can now see the sign pointing 
to this end of the trail.

42
00:04:09,600 --> 00:04:17,120
That means I've cycled thirteen kilometres 
in less than two hours. That's good. It will  

43
00:04:17,120 --> 00:04:23,920
give me more time to finish my hike back to the 
truck. I lock my bike to a tree and start walking.

44
00:04:25,360 --> 00:04:29,760
As I walk, I think about the history 
of the people who were here before me.  

45
00:04:30,880 --> 00:04:33,760
One of them, Butch Cassidy, was very famous.  

46
00:04:34,960 --> 00:04:41,920
He and his men stole horses and hid from the law 
during the last years of the nineteenth century.

47
00:04:41,920 --> 00:04:45,920
Since that time, the area has 
been called Robbers Roost country.

48
00:04:47,360 --> 00:04:53,600
My climbing bag is heavy with the weight of my 
equipment. I think about my plan for the day.  

49
00:04:54,720 --> 00:04:58,160
Blue John Canyon will be the 
most difficult part of the hike.

50
00:04:59,680 --> 00:05:03,120
Three kilometres along the 
trail is the Big Drop Rappel.

51
00:05:04,560 --> 00:05:12,720
Here, the canyon suddenly drops eighteen metres. 
The hardest part is 180 metres before this.  

52
00:05:13,840 --> 00:05:17,760
The walls there are very narrow 
and the trail goes up and down,  

53
00:05:17,760 --> 00:05:22,960
sharply. There are also a lot of 
very large rocks called boulders,  

54
00:05:22,960 --> 00:05:28,880
stuck between the canyon walls. If these 
boulders move or fall, they can be dangerous.

55
00:05:30,320 --> 00:05:32,800
But I'm not thinking of danger at the moment.  

56
00:05:33,920 --> 00:05:42,560
I am excited. Today, I will finally see the Great 
Gallery. The Gallery is part of Horseshoe Canyon,  

57
00:05:42,560 --> 00:05:49,200
and it's famous for the huge rock paintings which 
cover its walls. Some of them are more than five  

58
00:05:49,200 --> 00:05:57,040
thousand years old. I should reach my truck by 
late afternoon. So far, things are going well.  

59
00:05:58,160 --> 00:06:06,240
I arrived here earlier than I thought. This 
gives me a little more time to finish my trip.

60
00:06:06,240 --> 00:06:13,280
I always get very excited when I'm about to leave 
on a trip. This means I sometimes forget things.  

61
00:06:14,480 --> 00:06:20,720
Before starting this trip, I forgot to leave a 
message telling anyone exactly where I was going.  

62
00:06:21,760 --> 00:06:28,320
This is one of the things my mother taught me. 
But this time, I just called a quick goodbye to  

63
00:06:28,320 --> 00:06:37,920
my housemates - Brian, Joe, and Leona. Leona asked 
where I was going. I told her I was going to Utah  

64
00:06:37,920 --> 00:06:43,200
and promised to be back for her party. 
Then I got in my truck and drove away.

65
00:06:45,040 --> 00:06:52,400
I can't wait for adventure. It makes me feel 
happier than anything. It's part of who I am.

66
00:06:53,760 --> 00:06:59,840
I'm on a high rock, looking down at the 
trail. I've stopped because I can hear voices.  

67
00:07:00,960 --> 00:07:10,240
This surprises me. I had expected to be alone. 
Two young women suddenly appear below me. I feel  

68
00:07:10,240 --> 00:07:17,600
pleased. I've spent the last eighteen hours alone. 
It will be good to have company for a while.

69
00:07:19,360 --> 00:07:26,560
'Hi,' I call as I climb down the rock. 
The girls hadn't noticed me. They turn,  

70
00:07:26,560 --> 00:07:31,760
looking a little nervous. I guess 
they are about twenty-five years old.

71
00:07:33,120 --> 00:07:36,560
I smile and hold out my hand, 'My name's Aron.'

72
00:07:37,520 --> 00:07:43,840
They smile back. 'I'm Megan,' says 
the darker girl, 'and this is Kristi.'

73
00:07:44,560 --> 00:07:51,120
We shake hands and continue along the trail. 
As we go, we talk about our interests.  

74
00:07:52,160 --> 00:07:58,880
We all love hiking, biking and adventures. 
For all of us, this is more important than  

75
00:07:58,880 --> 00:08:06,400
earning a lot of money. They work in the same 
business, too. They work for Outward Bound,  

76
00:08:06,400 --> 00:08:14,400
a sports equipment shop in Moab, Utah. Both Aspen 
and Moab are important tourist centres for hikers.

77
00:08:16,000 --> 00:08:22,640
We are on the trail together for about five 
kilometres. At that point, there is a smaller  

78
00:08:22,640 --> 00:08:30,000
canyon to the west. The west canyon goes back 
in a half-circle. The girls left their bikes  

79
00:08:30,000 --> 00:08:36,320
at the end of it. We will say goodbye there and 
I'll continue on alone to the Big Drop Rappel.

80
00:08:37,760 --> 00:08:43,680
We arrive just before 2.00 pm. I 
don't feel like saying goodbye.  

81
00:08:44,720 --> 00:08:49,040
In the hour and a half we've been 
together, we've already become friends.

82
00:08:50,560 --> 00:08:55,600
Megan feels the same. 'Why don't 
you come with us?' she asks.  

83
00:08:56,640 --> 00:09:01,680
'We can finish the west canyon trail, go 
back to our truck and have a few beers.'

84
00:09:03,360 --> 00:09:10,160
I like the idea, but following my plan is 
more important. I ask them to come with me.

85
00:09:11,200 --> 00:09:15,200
'How far is it back to your truck?' Megan asks.

86
00:09:16,240 --> 00:09:18,240
'Around thirteen kilometres.'

87
00:09:19,680 --> 00:09:24,560
'That's too far. You won't get 
back before dark,' she says.

88
00:09:26,160 --> 00:09:29,600
'Maybe not, but I really want 
to do the Big Drop Rappel.  

89
00:09:30,640 --> 00:09:36,160
And I can't miss the paintings in the Great 
Gallery. I'll meet you after for a drink.'

90
00:09:37,680 --> 00:09:41,200
We agree on a plan to meet 
and go to the party together.

91
00:09:42,560 --> 00:09:50,160
Then I turn and wave goodbye. The movement is 
so easy I don't think about it. But there is  

92
00:09:50,160 --> 00:09:56,240
something I don't know. It is the last time 
I will wave goodbye with my right hand.
 
 
 

93
00:09:57,760 --> 00:09:58,480
CHAPTER TWO

94
00:09:59,600 --> 00:10:00,400
The accident

95
00:10:01,520 --> 00:10:08,080
The girls disappear into the west 
canyon. I am alone again. I continue  

96
00:10:08,080 --> 00:10:14,720
walking towards the Big Drop Rappel. It seems 
strangely quiet without Kristi and Megan.  

97
00:10:15,680 --> 00:10:22,320
I turn on my CD player and listen to a soft, 
slow song by Phish, one of my favourite bands.

98
00:10:23,760 --> 00:10:30,400
The music is perfect for the way I feel: 
lucky, free and happy. The weather is perfect,  

99
00:10:30,400 --> 00:10:35,440
too. It's warm and sunny with just 
a few white clouds in the sky.

100
00:10:37,120 --> 00:10:41,760
Suddenly, my feet hit a pile of loose 
stones and I nearly fall to the ground.

101
00:10:42,880 --> 00:10:44,160
Careful, Aron.

102
00:10:44,840 --> 00:10:51,600
I listen to the voice in my head and look up 
the canyon. I can see that the trail ahead  

103
00:10:51,600 --> 00:10:57,600
becomes more difficult. The Big Drop 
Rappel is now just under a kilometre away.

104
00:10:59,200 --> 00:11:03,520
Twenty minutes later, I arrive at 
the most difficult part of the trail.  

105
00:11:04,640 --> 00:11:11,840
Here, the canyon walls are a lot narrower. The 
trail rises and falls and is full of sharp rocks.  

106
00:11:12,960 --> 00:11:19,280
I will have to be careful. I look up and see 
part of a tree stuck between the canyon walls.  

107
00:11:20,320 --> 00:11:23,200
It was carried along the canyon after heavy rain.  

108
00:11:24,320 --> 00:11:30,080
This is one of the dangers of hiking in 
canyon country. After a sudden storm,  

109
00:11:30,080 --> 00:11:37,120
canyons can quickly fill with water. In seconds, 
the water can throw you against the canyon walls  

110
00:11:37,120 --> 00:11:43,040
and kill you. That's why it's always very 
important to check the weather before canyoning.

111
00:11:44,800 --> 00:11:50,640
Just below the tree is the first drop in 
the trail. It's only about three metres,  

112
00:11:51,200 --> 00:11:56,080
so I won't need any equipment. There 
are plenty of holes in the rock  

113
00:11:56,080 --> 00:11:59,120
for my hands and feet so I climb down easily.  

114
00:12:00,160 --> 00:12:07,040
A metre from the bottom I let go and land on the 
ground. Soft sand covers the tops of my boots.  

115
00:12:08,240 --> 00:12:15,440
From here, it would be difficult to climb back up. 
One thing is immediately clear: I can't go back.

116
00:12:16,880 --> 00:12:24,320
The canyon walls become even narrower. Stuck 
between them, as far as I can see, are boulders  

117
00:12:24,320 --> 00:12:31,760
of different sizes. It's an unusual sight. I 
stop and take a few pictures with my camera.

118
00:12:33,200 --> 00:12:37,840
The Big Drop Rappel is now 
only about 160 metres away.  

119
00:12:39,360 --> 00:12:47,200
Climbing down will be no problem. I have all 
the equipment I need in my backpack. For food,  

120
00:12:47,200 --> 00:12:54,320
I have two burritos. I also have a full water 
bottle and an extra two litres in a CamelBak.

121
00:12:55,760 --> 00:13:02,000
The boulders are both good and bad news. The 
good news is that I should be able to climb  

122
00:13:02,000 --> 00:13:07,760
over many of them. This will be quicker than 
dropping on to the trail and climbing back up  

123
00:13:07,760 --> 00:13:14,080
again. The bad news is that the boulders 
could move. I will have to be careful.

124
00:13:15,520 --> 00:13:21,920
I manage the first few boulders without any 
problems and reach another drop. This one  

125
00:13:21,920 --> 00:13:27,840
is about four metres down. About three metres 
from the edge of the drop is a boulder.  

126
00:13:28,720 --> 00:13:31,520
It's about the same size as the wheel of a bus.  

127
00:13:32,720 --> 00:13:39,200
If I climb onto it, the drop from there will be 
shorter. I chimney to the boulder quite easily.

128
00:13:40,640 --> 00:13:48,000
As I stand on it, I feel something move. 
The movement stops almost immediately.  

129
00:13:48,000 --> 00:13:54,160
It seems there's nothing to worry about. 
I lie down, put my hands in two holes on  

130
00:13:54,160 --> 00:13:59,040
the far edge of the boulder and push my 
legs over the opposite side to jump down.

131
00:14:00,560 --> 00:14:05,520
As most of my weight pushes on one side 
of the boulder, it makes a strange sound.  

132
00:14:06,640 --> 00:14:12,880
Immediately I know this is trouble but 
it's too late to go back. From this point,  

133
00:14:12,880 --> 00:14:19,280
everything seems to happen very slowly. I let 
go of the boulder and drop towards the ground.  

134
00:14:20,400 --> 00:14:24,560
As I fall, I look up and see the 
boulder crashing towards my head.  

135
00:14:25,600 --> 00:14:32,240
If I don't get out of the way, I'm dead. I try 
to push against the boulder with both hands.  

136
00:14:33,280 --> 00:14:39,440
It hits my left hand hard against the canyon 
wall. I pull it back with a scream of pain.  

137
00:14:40,480 --> 00:14:45,680
The boulder then hits my right arm and traps 
my hand against the right side of the canyon.
 
 

138
00:14:47,520 --> 00:14:48,400
6 hrs

139
00:14:49,760 --> 00:14:57,840
2.45 pm All this happens in a couple of seconds. 
I don't even notice landing on the canyon floor.  

140
00:14:58,640 --> 00:15:05,600
I am so shocked I feel no pain. I just stand 
there, looking at my trapped hand in disbelief.

141
00:15:07,040 --> 00:15:15,120
Stupid, Aron, stupid! When you first stood on 
the rock, it moved. That was a clear message to  

142
00:15:15,120 --> 00:15:20,640
stay away! But you were in such a hurry to 
finish the hike you didn't stop and check.

143
00:15:22,080 --> 00:15:26,640
The voice in my head doesn't 
help. It just makes things worse.

144
00:15:28,160 --> 00:15:36,320
A terrible pain travels up my arm. I scream 
and pull hard to try and free myself. Nothing  

145
00:15:36,320 --> 00:15:44,080
happens. I try again. This time I push against 
the boulder with my knees at the same time.

146
00:15:45,440 --> 00:15:49,680
It's no good. The boulder 
is a lot heavier than I am.

147
00:15:50,720 --> 00:15:53,840
I am stuck and there's no way out.
 
 
 

148
00:15:53,840 --> 00:15:54,640
CHAPTER THREE

149
00:15:55,840 --> 00:15:56,640
Three plans

150
00:15:57,840 --> 00:16:03,200
Stop thinking about how bad the problem 
is, Aron. You need to be sensible.

151
00:16:04,560 --> 00:16:12,160
The voice in my head is right. I must be 
sensible. This has to be my rule from now on.

152
00:16:13,520 --> 00:16:18,560
The first thing I need is a 
drink. Without stopping to think,  

153
00:16:18,560 --> 00:16:22,880
I take the water bottle from my bag and 
drink a third of it in five seconds.

154
00:16:24,320 --> 00:16:28,480
I suddenly realise what I'm doing 
and pull the bottle out of my mouth.  

155
00:16:29,680 --> 00:16:32,880
Already, I have broken my rule to be sensible.

156
00:16:34,160 --> 00:16:36,960
I have no idea how long I will be here.  

157
00:16:38,000 --> 00:16:41,760
This means that the most important 
thing of all is to save water.

158
00:16:42,880 --> 00:16:50,160
Damn it, Aron! Stupid! Stupid! Stupid!
 
 

159
00:16:50,160 --> 00:16:52,000
6 hrs 43 mins

160
00:16:53,920 --> 00:16:58,160
3.28 pm It's almost forty-five 
minutes since my accident.  

161
00:16:59,280 --> 00:17:06,320
I am calmer than before. For the last half hour, 
I've been thinking of my best chance of escape.  

162
00:17:07,200 --> 00:17:13,760
I said I would meet Kristi and Megan after the 
hike. If I don't appear, will they go to my  

163
00:17:13,760 --> 00:17:21,200
truck to find me? I won't be there. But will they 
realise that something is wrong and go for help?

164
00:17:22,640 --> 00:17:27,840
The answer is probably 'no'. Kristi 
and Megan don't know me very well.  

165
00:17:29,040 --> 00:17:31,840
They'll just think that I 
decided not to meet them.  

166
00:17:32,880 --> 00:17:40,720
What about other hikers? Will they find me by 
chance? Again, the answer is probably 'no'.  

167
00:17:41,920 --> 00:17:48,800
Very few people travel to the Great Gallery from 
this end of the trail. My friends won't worry,  

168
00:17:48,800 --> 00:17:56,080
either. They weren't completely sure I was 
going to the party. Even on Monday evening,  

169
00:17:56,080 --> 00:18:02,880
my housemates will just think I'm late getting 
back. No one will miss me until Tuesday morning.  

170
00:18:03,920 --> 00:18:09,440
When I don't arrive for work, Brion After, 
my boss, will know that something is wrong.  

171
00:18:10,560 --> 00:18:15,520
I am never late for work. He will 
probably call my family and they  

172
00:18:15,520 --> 00:18:22,560
will tell the police that I am missing. But I 
didn't tell anyone exactly where I was going,  

173
00:18:23,200 --> 00:18:29,600
so it will take the police days to find me. 
If I don't escape before then, I will die.

174
00:18:31,120 --> 00:18:35,840
All of this means that I will have 
to get out of here alone. But how?

175
00:18:37,120 --> 00:18:43,280
I can think of three possible plans. The 
first plan is to use the large knife on the  

176
00:18:43,280 --> 00:18:49,360
multi-tool to chip at the boulder. This might 
take away enough of the rock to free my hand.  

177
00:18:50,480 --> 00:18:57,280
The second plan is to try and lift the boulder 
using some of my equipment. The third plan is  

178
00:18:57,280 --> 00:19:05,200
the worst. I could amputate my arm using the 
multi-tool. It's too soon to think of that idea.

179
00:19:06,800 --> 00:19:16,160
I try plan one. I take the multi-tool from my 
climbing bag. It has two knives. One is longer  

180
00:19:16,160 --> 00:19:24,560
than the other. I use the longest one, which is 
not so sharp. To free my hand, I must remove a  

181
00:19:24,560 --> 00:19:31,200
piece of rock over fifteen centimetres wide and 
seven centimetres deep. That's a lot of rock.
 
 

182
00:19:32,880 --> 00:19:34,480
10 hrs 15 mins

183
00:19:36,320 --> 00:19:44,160
7.0 pm I've been chipping at the rock for almost 
three and a half hours. I stop for a drink of  

184
00:19:44,160 --> 00:19:51,600
water. I lay the multi-tool on the boulder and 
reach for the water bottle. This time I am more  

185
00:19:51,600 --> 00:19:58,080
careful and take only a sip. I wonder how long 
I'll be able to survive with the water I have  

186
00:19:58,080 --> 00:20:06,400
left, only two-thirds of a litre. Until Monday 
night, maybe? Tuesday morning at the latest.
 
 
 

187
00:20:07,920 --> 00:20:08,640
CHAPTER FOUR

188
00:20:09,920 --> 00:20:10,720
Night and day

189
00:20:11,840 --> 00:20:16,240
After Kristi and Megan left Aron, 
they got lost in the west canyon  

190
00:20:16,240 --> 00:20:20,560
and arrived late at the 
meeting place. He wasn't there.

191
00:20:22,240 --> 00:20:26,480
'He's probably left already,' said 
Megan, 'but he can't be far away.  

192
00:20:27,680 --> 00:20:30,480
Let's drive around and see if we can find him.'

193
00:20:31,920 --> 00:20:34,640
But there was no sign of Aron or his bike.  

